05295nam a22007935i 9780520961869DE-B159720200424112023.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200424t20152015cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209618697 a10.1525/97805209618692doi  a(DE-B1597)519491  a(OCoLC)920088505  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aPS1331b.A2 2015 7aLIT0040202bisacsh04a818/.4092231 aTwain, Mark, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aAutobiography of Mark Twain, Volume 3 :bThe Complete and Authoritative Edition /cMark Twain; Harriet E. Smith, Benjamin Griffin. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2015] 4cÂ©2015  a1 online resource (792 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aMark Twain Papers ;v1200tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tLIST OF DICTATIONS -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tDictated March 1, 1907- Dictated December 12, 1907 -- tDictated January 13, 1908- Dictated Christmas Day, 1908 -- tDictated at Stormfield, January 5, 1909- Dictated October 21, 1909 -- tTHE ASHCROFT-LYON MANUSCRIPT -- tEXPLANATORY NOTES -- tAPPENDIXES -- tNOTE ON THE TEXT -- tWORD DIVISION IN THIS VOLUME -- tREFERENCES -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe surprising final chapter of a great American life. When the first volume of Mark Twain's uncensored Autobiography was published in 2010, it was hailed as an essential addition to the shelf of his works and a crucial document for our understanding of the great humorist's life and times. This third and final volume crowns and completes his life's work. Like its companion volumes, it chronicles Twain's inner and outer life through a series of daily dictations that go wherever his fancy leads. Created from March 1907 to December 1909, these dictations present Mark Twain at the end of his life: receiving an honorary degree from Oxford University; railing against Theodore Roosevelt; founding numerous clubs; incredulous at an exhibition of the Holy Grail; credulous about the authorship of Shakespeare's plays; relaxing in Bermuda; observing (and investing in) new technologies. The Autobiography's "Closing Words" movingly commemorate his daughter Jean, who died on Christmas Eve 1909. Also included in this volume is the previously unpublished "Ashcroft-Lyon Manuscript," Mark Twain's caustic indictment of his "putrescent pair" of secretaries and the havoc that erupted in his house during their residency. Fitfully published in fragments at intervals throughout the twentieth century, Autobiography of Mark Twain has now been critically reconstructed and made available as it was intended to be read. Fully annotated by the editors of the Mark Twain Project, the complete Autobiography emerges as a landmark publication in American literature. Editors: Benjamin Griffin and Harriet Elinor Smith Associate Editors: Victor Fischer, Michael B. Frank, Amanda Gagel, Sharon K. Goetz, Leslie Diane Myrick, Christopher M. Ohge  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aAuthors, Americany19th centuryvBiography. 4aamerican historian. 4aamerican history. 4aamerican literature. 4aatypical memoir. 4aautobiography. 4adaily dictations. 4aenglish professor. 4agreat american writers. 4ahistorical figures. 4ahumorist. 4aliterary history. 4amark twain project. 4amemoir. 4anotable american figures. 4apen name. 4apseudonym. 4asouthern history. 4athird volume. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / American / General.2bisacsh1 aGriffin, Benjamin, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSmith, Harriet E., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package 2000-2015z978311066334108iTitle is part of eBook